    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if it's just the capacitor, it's basically like the motor is trying to start but can't get the boost it needs? is there any way to tell if it's actually blown just by looking at it, or do i need tools to test it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a great analogy - think of the capacitor like a spark that energizes the motor. If the capacitor is bad, the motor's startup process can be disrupted, leading to the symptoms you're experiencing.\n\nTo diagnose a blown capacitor, you can look for visual signs such as a darkened or corroded appearance. A faulty capacitor can also crack, burn, or rupture, but this is uncommon and often indicates a more severe electrical issue.\n\nHowever, to confirm whether a capacitor is blown, it's usually necessary to use a multimeter to measure the capacitor's resistance and voltage. A multimeter can detect a capacitor's malfunction, and if you're not comfortable using one, it's recommended to consult a professional HVAC technician to ensure your safety.",
